  "prompt": "How do calculate the gear ratio?",
  "response": "To calculate the gear ratio, you'll need to understand the relationship between two meshing gears. The gear ratio is determined by comparing the number of teeth on each gear.\n\nHere\u2019s a detailed step-by-step method:\n\n1. **Identify the Gears**: Establish which gear is the driver (the gear providing the input force) and which is the driven gear (the gear receiving the input force).\n\n2. **Count the Teeth**: Count the number of teeth on both the driver and driven gears.\n\n3. **Calculate the Gear Ratio**: Use the formula:\n\n   \\[\n   \\text{Gear Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Number of Teeth on Driven Gear}}{\\text{Number of Teeth on Driver Gear}}\n   \\]\n\n   Alternatively, if you are dealing with pulleys or sprockets where diameters are more relevant, you can use the diameters instead:\n\n   \\[\n   \\text{Gear Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Diameter of Driven Gear}}{\\text{Diameter of Driver Gear}}\n   \\]\n\n4. **Interpret the Result**: \n   - If the gear ratio is greater than 1, the output speed (of the driven gear) is slower than the input speed (driver gear), but the torque is increased.\n   - If the gear ratio is less than 1, the output speed is faster than the input speed, but the torque is decreased.\n\n**Example**: If a motor turns a driver gear with 10 teeth, which meshes with a driven gear with 20 teeth:\n\n   \\[\n   \\text{Gear Ratio} = \\frac{20}{10} = 2:1\n   \\]\n\nThis means the driven gear turns once for every two turns of the driver gear, resulting in a decrease in speed and an increase in torque for the driven gear.",
